text: Abstract
label: H4

text: High power density electronic components such as fast microprocessors and power semiconductors must
label: BODY

text: operate below the maximum rated device junction temperature to ensure reliability. Junction temperatures are
label: BODY

text: determined by the amount of heat generated and the thermal resistance from junction to the ambient thermal
label: BODY

text: environment. Two of the largest contributions to this thermal resistance are the die attach interface and the package
label: BODY

text: base. A decrease in these resistances can allow increased component packing density in MCMs, reduction of heat
label: BODY

text: sink volume in tightly packed systems, enable the use of higher performance circuit components, and improve
label: BODY

text: reliability.
label: BODY

text: The substrate for high power density devices is the primary thermal link between the junctions and the heat
label: BODY

text: sink. Present high power multichip modules and single chip packages use substrate materials such as silicon nitride
label: BODY

text: or copper tungsten that have thermal conductivity in the range of 200 W/mK. We have developed Dymalloy, a
label: BODY

text: copper-diamond composite, that has a thermal conductivity of 420 W/mK and an adjustable coefficient of thermal
label: BODY

text: expansion, nominally 5.5 ppm/C at 25 C, compatible with silicon and gallium arsenide. Because of the matched
label: BODY

text: coefficient of thermal expansion it is possible to use low thermal resistance hard die attach methods.
label: BODY

text: Dymalloy is a composite material made using micron size Type I diamond powder that has a published
label: BODY

text: thermal conductivity of 600 to 1000 W/mK  in a metal matrix that has a thermal conductivity of 350 W/mK. The
label: BODY

text: region of chemical bonding between the matrix material and diamond is limited to approximately 100 A to maintain
label: BODY

text: a high effective thermal conductivity for the composite. The material may be fabricated in near net shapes.
label: BODY

text: Besides having exceptional thermal properties, the mechanical properties of this material also make it an
label: BODY

text: attractive candidate as an electronic component substrate material.
label: BODY

text: Key words: substrate, package base, composite material, diamond composite
label: BODY

text: Introduction
label: HH3

text: Modern microprocessors have reached
label: BODY

text: power densities of 77 W/cm2 [1], and are
label: BODY

text: predicted to rise to 200 W/cm2 [2]. Power
label: BODY

text: semiconductors, such as the die in a 350 W
label: BODY

text: BUS50 TO-3 power transistor, may operate at a
label: BODY

text: power density of 660 W/cm2 [3]. To ensure
label: BODY

text: correct operation and adequate life it is
label: BODY

text: necessary to limit the junction temperature to
label: BODY

text: less than 200 C for discrete power
label: BODY

text: semiconductors, 125 C for military logic devices,
label: BODY

text: and as low as 70 C for some commercial logic
label: BODY

text: devices. For many high power density devices
label: BODY

text: much of the allowable temperature budget is
label: BODY

text: expended in the package base and die attach
label: BODY

text: thermal resistances.
label: BODY

text: The ideal material for a package base
label: BODY

text: would have infinite thermal conductivity and a
label: BODY

text: CTE perfectly matched to the semiconductor
label: BODY

text: material. The need for high thermal conductivity
label: BODY

text: is obvious. The good CTE match is required
label: BODY

text: because thermally induced shear stress at the die
label: BODY

text: bond is directly proportional to the mismatch in
label: BODY

text: CTE and the length from the center of the die to
label: BODY

text: a corner.
label: BODY

text: The best thermal conductivity available
label: BODY

text: in a naturally occurring material is about 2200
label: BODY

text: W/mK for good quality Type IIa diamond. Pure
label: BODY

text: copper has a thermal conductivity of 393
label: BODY

text: W/mK. Common package base materials such
label: BODY

text: as copper-tungsten, AlN, and BeO all have
label: BODY

text: thermal conductivities near 200 W/mK. The
label: BODY

text: new aluminum silicon carbide composites also
label: BODY

text: fall in this range. Copper diamond composite
label: BODY

text: material, called Dymalloy, made with 55 vol% of
label: BODY

text: good quality Type I diamond has a thermal
label: BODY

text: conductivity of 420 W/mK.
label: BODY

text: While Type IIa diamond has been
label: BODY

text: successfully employed as a heat spreader for
label: BODY

text: laser diodes and some microwave devices, its
label: BODY

text: CTE of 1.7 ppm/C, compared to 5.8 ppm/C for
label: BODY

text: GaAs, limits its use with hard, high thermal
label: BODY

text: conductivity, die attach methods to die generally
label: BODY

text: less than 1 mm on a side. Dymalloy, made with
label: BODY

text: 55 vol% diamond, has a perfect CTE match to
label: BODY

text: gallium arsenide. Note that siightly increasing
label: BODY

text: the diamond volume fraction allows the CTE to
label: BODY

text: be adjusted to provide a perfect match to silicon.
label: BODY

text: Values of the thermal conductivity and CTE of
label: BODY

text: common semiconductor and substrate materials
label: BODY

text: are shown in Table 1.
label: BODY

text: As an example consider a die with a
label: BODY

text: power density of 100 W/cm2 attached to a
label: BODY

text: substrate with a 65 µ bond line. Using a silver-
label: BODY

text: filled epoxy die attach will result in a
label: BODY

text: temperature rise of  29C. Using a Au-Sn bond
label: BODY

text: would result in a rise of 0.8 C. This is smaller
label: BODY

text: than the 4.4 C rise through a typical 625 µ thick
label: BODY

text: silicon die under these conditions. For extremely
label: BODY

text: high power density conditions combining
label: BODY

text: thinned die with an activated nitride bond
label: BODY

text: process [4] that can produce a bond line only
label: BODY

text: 2000 A thick may be appropriate.

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Given that the total temperature rise
label: BODY

text: budget from junction to ambient is only 60 C in
label: BODY

text: the case of workstations, having a substrate that
label: BODY

text: is CTE matched to the semiconductor provides a
label: BODY

text: major advantage. Using a substrate with more
label: BODY

text: that twice the thermal conductivity of any other
label: BODY

text: CTE matched material provides additional
label: BODY

text: margin.
label: BODY

text: Fabrication Considerations
label: HH3

text: The fabrication process for Dymalloy,  a
label: BODY

text: high thermal conductivity diamond-metal
label: BODY

text: composite, was developed to address both
label: BODY

text: technical and commercial requirements. The
label: BODY

text: technical challenge is to combine diamond
label: BODY

text: powders with a metal to produce a composite
label: BODY

text: with high thermal conductivity. The commercial
label: BODY

text: requirements are to produce this composite in
label: BODY

text: near net shape and to be cost competitive with
label: BODY

text: existing products. These two basic requirements
label: BODY

text: have guided the development of Dymalloy.
label: BODY

text: In order to be cost competitive the
label: BODY

text: diamond powder and metal matrix material
label: BODY

text: must be readily available and both must have
label: BODY

text: high thermal conductivity. The ideal diamond
label: BODY

text: powder material would be free from defects and
label: BODY

text: contaminants. These requirements are
label: BODY

text: approached by Type IIa diamonds that have a
label: BODY

text: typical thermal conductivity of 2200 W/mK.
label: BODY

text: Type IIa diamonds are used for jewelry and are
label: BODY

text: unavailable in powder form. CVD diamond
label: BODY

text: films are the next choice for the composite with a
label: BODY

text: thermal conductivity of 1400 W/mK. These
label: BODY

text: films could be crushed into powders for the
label: BODY

text: composite but this process is not economically
label: BODY

text: feasible. The more common Type I diamond is
label: BODY

text: commercially available as powder and is used
label: BODY

text: for manufacturing operations such as grinding
label: BODY

text: and lapping. Type I diamond has a measured
label: BODY

text: thermal conductivity of 600 to 1000 W/mK and
label: BODY

text: costs between $0.50 and $1.00 a carat. Type I
label: BODY

text: diamond powder is used to make Dymalloy
label: BODY

text: because of its availability and cost.
label: BODY

text: The reported thermal conductivity of
label: BODY

text: diamond was measured on relatively large
label: BODY

text: diamond samples and not on the diamond
label: BODY

text: powder used for the composite.  The bulk
label: BODY

text: thermal conductivity of a material is size
label: BODY

text: independent until the dimensions of the material
label: BODY

text: approach the mean free path of the heat
label: BODY

text: transport mechanism, electrons for metals and
label: BODY

text: phonons for non-metals. The minimum size
label: BODY

text: diamond powder used in the composite was
label: BODY

text: estimated to be at least ten times the phonon
label: BODY

text: mean free path in the diamond or approximately
label: BODY

text: 1 µ.  Graebner et.al. [5] showed that diamond
label: BODY

text: grain size affects the thermal conductivity of
label: BODY

text: CVD diamond films. As the grainsize increases
label: BODY

text: the thermal conductivity increases until the
label: BODY

text: grains are larger than approximately 20 µ.
label: BODY

text: Dymalloy has been made with diamond
label: BODY

text: powders in the 6 to 50 µ size range.
label: BODY

text: The variation in Type I diamond
label: BODY

text: thermal conductivity is also a function of purity
label: BODY

text: and internal defects. Diamond powders may
label: BODY

text: containa variety of metal impurities and a
label: BODY

text: variable amount of nitrogen. Some diamond
label: BODY

text: powders are manufactured to have a high
label: BODY

text: density of internal defects.
label: BODY

text: For our application Type I diamond
label: BODY

text: powder material should be selected to maximize
label: BODY

text: the thermal characteristics of the composite.
label: BODY

text: Dymalloy was made using diamond powders
label: BODY

text: purchased from several vendors in order to
label: BODY

text: optimize the composite properties.
label: BODY

text: Obtaining a high thermal conductivity
label: BODY

text: diamond composite substrate requires that the
label: BODY

text: diamond be chemically bonded to the matrix
label: BODY

text: material. At the bond line between the metal
label: BODY

text: matrix and diamond the metal electron thermal
label: BODY

text: conductivity is converted into phonon
label: BODY

text: conductivity. There is some evidence that the
label: BODY

text: bonding material can affect this transition [6].
label: BODY

text: This is critical because the metal-carbon bond, or
label: BODY

text: carbide, has relatively poor thermal
label: BODY

text: conductivity. To minimize this effect the total
label: BODY

text: thickness of this bond must be minimized.
label: BODY

text: Materials such as titanium, tungsten, chrome,
label: BODY

text: and zirconium have been used to form the
label: BODY

text: carbide bond in Dymalloy. The majority of
label: BODY

text: Dymalloy composites have been made using
label: BODY

text: Tungsten - 26 % Rhenium as the bond material.
label: BODY

text: Quantitative measurements of the effect of
label: BODY

text: various bond material have not been made so
label: BODY

text: the choice of using W-Rh is qualitative, based on
label: BODY

text: observations during the fabrication process.
label: BODY

text: Fabrication of Dymalloy
label: BODY

text: The first step in the fabrication process
label: BODY

text: is  coating the diamond powder using a physical
label: BODY

text: vapor deposition technique. To ensure uniform
label: BODY

text: coating of the irregular diamond grains the
label: BODY

text: powder is tumbled in the coating system. This is
label: BODY

text: accomplished by placing the powder in a small
label: BODY

text: metal pan that is mechanically vibrated in the
label: BODY

text: vertical direction by a piezo-ceramic transducer.
label: BODY

text: The diamond is coated in this system with
label: BODY

text: approximately 100 A of W-Rh . We have verified
label: BODY

text: this thickness using TEM analysis.
label: BODY

text: All of the carbide forming materials
label: BODY

text: oxidize in air and bonding to oxide surfaces is
label: BODY

text: difficult. This problem is prevented by coating
label: BODY

text: 1000 A of a brazeable material, such as pure
label: BODY

text: copper, on top of the carbide former in situ. The
label: BODY

text: result is coated diamond powder that has 100 A
label: BODY

text: of a carbide forming material overcoated with
label: BODY

text: 1000 A of brazeable material.
label: BODY

text: At this point the coated diamond
label: BODY

text: powder can be packed into a form and vacuum
label: BODY

text: infiltrated with the metal matrix material to
label: BODY

text: form a composite. Although composites have
label: BODY

text: been made using this technique, the diamond
label: BODY

text: powder with these very thin coatings are
label: BODY

text: difficult to form into a final shape before
label: BODY

text: infiltrating. Control samples made using
label: BODY

text: commercially available copper coated diamond
label: BODY

text: powder were not as difficult to form. The
label: BODY

text: commercial coated diamond powder has a
label: BODY

text: thicker copper coating, several microns thick,
label: BODY

text: that flows during the forming process. Although
label: BODY

text: the commercial powder is easier to form,
label: BODY

text: examination of this powder shows that the
label: BODY

text: diamond grains are entrapped, not bonded, in
label: BODY

text: the copper. An electroless plating process is
label: BODY

text: used to increase the copper thickness to several
label: BODY

text: microns on the coated diamond powder used for
label: BODY

text: making Dymalloy. This added step makes the
label: BODY

text: forming process easier.
label: BODY

text: The composite is made by placing the
label: BODY

text: powder into a form, pressing the powder to the
label: BODY

text: desired thickness, and infiltrating with the
label: BODY

text: matrix material. This forming process was
label: BODY

text: developed using commercially available copper
label: BODY

text: coated diamond powder. The data from this
label: BODY

text: development is directly applicable to making
label: BODY

text: Dymalloy. Experiments were made to determine
label: BODY

text: the initial filling thickness of diamond powder,
label: BODY

text: the pressure necessary to compact the form, and
label: BODY

text: the amount of metal matrix material that is
label: BODY

text: needed for the infiltration process so that the
label: BODY

text: final composite meets thickness and
label: BODY

text: dimensional tolerances.
label: BODY

text: The final step is infiltrating the formed
label: BODY

text: diamond powder with a high thermal
label: BODY

text: conductivity material. We presently use a
label: BODY

text: copper-silver (20/80) alloy that has a thermal
label: BODY

text: conductivity of 354 W/mK and a melting point
label: BODY

text: of approximately 800 C. Other materials such as
label: BODY

text: copper with a thermal conductivity of 393
label: BODY

text: W/mK can be used, but the lower melting
label: BODY

text: temperature alloy avoids problems with
label: BODY

text: graphitization of the diamond.
label: BODY

text: The infiltration process is done in a
label: BODY

text: vacuum and capillary action allows the metal
label: BODY

text: braze to wick into the form. Using an amount of
label: BODY

text: braze material just sufficient to thoroughly wet
label: BODY

text: the form ensures that the composite does not
label: BODY

text: deform upon cooling due to the differences in
label: BODY

text: the coefficient of thermal expansion between the
label: BODY

text: braze material and the composite. Other
label: BODY

text: manufacturing processes that combine sections
label: BODY

text: of these last two steps can be envisioned but
label: BODY

text: were  not tried.
label: BODY

text: Material Properties
label: BODY

text: The material properties that have been
label: BODY

text: measured include density, porosity, diamond
label: BODY

text: fraction, specific heat, coefficient of thermal
label: BODY

text: expansion, thermal conductivity, speed of
label: BODY

text: sound, and the mechanical stress - strain
label: BODY

text: relation. Some of the properties such as density,
label: BODY

text: specific heat, and the coefficient of thermal
label: BODY

text: expansion can be determined from a rule of
label: BODY

text: mixtures formula assuming the volume fraction
label: BODY

text: of diamond in the composite and are verified by
label: BODY

text: measurements. These estimates also assume that
label: BODY

text: the composite is fully dense.
label: BODY

text: The diamond volume fraction is
label: BODY

text: determined by measuring the porosity and
label: BODY

text: density. We determined that the composite was
label: BODY

text: fully dense by using mercury porosimetry
label: BODY

text: technique. Any porosity would have a
label: BODY

text: detrimental affect on the thermal conductivity of
label: BODY

text: the composite. The measured density of 6.4 g/cc
label: BODY

text: was then used to determine the diamond
label: BODY

text: volume fraction of 55%.
label: BODY

text: Both the specific heat and the coefficient
label: BODY

text: of thermal expansion for several test pieces were
label: BODY

text: measured as functions of temperature. The
label: BODY

text: average specific heat for temperatures between
label: BODY

text: 25 and 75 C was measured to be 0.316 +
label: BODY

text: 8.372x10-4 T (J/gK). The average CTE between
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: many parallel and series conduction paths. A
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: conductivity of the composite, assuming the
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: effective thermal conductivity of the composite
label: BODY

text: can be made using the formula given in [7].

text: The speed of sound and the stress -
label: BODY

text: strain relation are difficult to estimate but they
label: BODY

text: were measured. Ultrasound techniques were
label: BODY

text: used to measure the speed of sound at 7000 m/s
label: BODY

text: in the copper diamond matrix material. This
label: BODY

text: sound speed is comparable to aluminum,
label: BODY

text: molybdenum, titanium, tungsten carbide, and
label: BODY

text: calcium fluoride. The stress strain relation for
label: BODY

text: Dymalloy shows that the material does have
label: BODY

text: some plastic characteristics. Dymalloy has a
label: BODY

text: linear stress-strain relation for stresses up to 40
label: BODY

text: kpsi and strains of approximately 0.1 to 0.2 %.
label: BODY

text: After this linear region the stress increases and
label: BODY

text: failure occurs between 50 and 60 kpsi at strains
label: BODY

text: of approximately 5.0 to 6.0 %.  Examination of
label: BODY

text: the fractured surfaces, shown in the magnified
label: BODY

text: portion of Figure 3, shows that brittle fracture
label: BODY

text: occurs in the diamonds and the matrix fails in a
label: BODY

text: ductile manner. The stress-strain relation shows
label: BODY

text: that Dymalloy is not a brittle material but has
label: BODY

text: some plastic characteristics which could prove
label: BODY

text: to be advantageous for manufacturing purposes.
label: BODY

text: Because Dymalloy is fabricated using a
label: BODY

text: powder process it is straightforward to process
label: BODY

text: components to near-net shape. The as fabricated
label: BODY

text: surface has some texture from the embedded
label: BODY

text: diamond particles. If a smoother surface is
label: BODY

text: required it is possible to plate up the surface and
label: BODY

text: polish it.

text: Conclusion
label: H4

text: Dymalloy has been developed as a
label: BODY

text: substrate material for use in high power density
